    "chunk_text": "Public Rights Movement raises alarm over Litro tender changes, calls for probe\n\nThe National Movement for the Protection of Public Rights has voiced strong concern over recent changes made to Litro Gas Lanka\u2019s tender process for importing liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), warning that the move could undermine the profitability of the State-owned enterprise (SOE) and compromise national energy security.\n\nIn a letter addressed to the Commission to Investigate Allegations of Bribery or Corruption (CIABOC) Director-General, Movement Convener Charaka Thilakaratne alleged that a key clause in previous tender documents had been removed without proper authorisation. The clause had prohibited Litro from using storage facilities owned by competing suppliers to store imported gas reserves, a safeguard long considered essential to prevent market manipulation in the critical gas sector.\n\n\u201cLitro, which played a vital role during the recent economic crisis, has been one of the few profitable SOEs in recent years. Its success stood as an example of how public enterprises can function without being a burden on the taxpayer,\u201d the letter noted. The Movement warned that the removal of the clause would carry far-reaching consequences, including eroding Litro\u2019s profitability, weakening State control over domestic gas prices, and enabling private competitors to gain market dominance.\n\nIt also charged that the tender changes were made after the announcement without approval from the Cabinet, Parliament, or a duly authorised committee. \u201cThis raises serious questions of corruption. It appears that decisions are being taken to intentionally benefit private players at the expense of the State and the public,\u201d they charged.\n\nThe Movement charged the Government of inconsistency, pointing out that it had repeatedly pledged to safeguard public ownership and control in the energy sector, while allegedly allowing practices that could hand disproportionate influence to private firms."
