    "description": "Retired Judges Should Not Perform Any Function For Personal Gain: Lawyers Collective",
    "url_metadata": "https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/retired-judges-should-not-perform-any-function-for-personal-gain-lawyers-collective/",
    "lang": "en",
    "newspaper_id": "colombotelegraphcom",
    "time_ut": 1740937862.0,
    "chunk_id": "2025-03-02-colombotelegraphcom-7488cd77-0000",
    "chunk_index": 0,
    "language": "en",
    "md5": "d82883a746b4a7e2f2d1ebac2577d8e9",
    "chunk_size_bytes": 1753,
    "chunk_text": "Retired Judges Should Not Perform Any Function For Personal Gain: Lawyers Collective\n\nLawyers Collective on the appointment of retired judges to positions in the public and private sectors\n\nThe appointment of retired judges, especially of the Superior Courts, to positions in both the public and private sectors has been a matter of concern to the legal community and the general public in Sri Lanka and elsewhere. Post-retirement appointments of judges create a cloud over the sanctity of their judgments, irrespective of their merits. They also tend to undermine public faith in judicial independence. It is worse when an appointment is made immediately after retirement.\n\nThis is not to say that the valuable experience and insights acquired by judges should be wasted after retirement. The country must make good use of their knowledge in a manner that does not raise the suspicion that they were not impartial during their tenure. There can be no objection to retired judges being appointed as members or Chairpersons of constitutional commissions, Commissions of Inquiry or institutions such as the Law Commission of Sri Lanka, provided they are appointed through mechanisms such as the Constitutional Council, which ensures a national consensus on appointments. Their expertise could also be used in legal education and training of judges and lawyers.\n\nThe Lawyers Collective proposes that retirement benefits for judges of the Superior Courts should be equivalent to the emoluments and benefits of judges in service. They should not perform any function that would bring them monetary gain, advantage, or benefit except as permitted by the Constitution or written law. These matters should be regulated by constitutional or statutory provisions."
